node.text:
Reflect with us 💭

🗣 Join the conversation between Sage and Jazz (@just_found_out_im_hot ) about the intersection of queer identity and disability with kink/rope. This is an important discussion that we hope you can learn something from. 

🤟🏼 Huge thank you to @the.blaike for ASL interpretation for this LIVE! 

🖊 The comment section is open for questions, thoughts or feedback.

🔏 Please be kind and mindful of the language that you use! We welcome conflict or disagreement as an opportunity for deeper relationship building and also ask that you try to hold other perspectives to be true and valid at the same time as yours. 

@authenticallysage 
@callme.sage 🌿💕

Join us for a discussion about our ongoing Monday DEI spaces with @authenticallysage @callme.sage 💕

Marika and Sage discuss why we are hosting DEI discussions on Monday and what makes this such an important part of community and collective liberation building. We are so excited to have this work on our platform and hope you will join us in these discussions. 

We look forward to building with you, learning along side you and creating change together. 🙏🏼

The practice of Hashira Shibari draws its inspiration from the very architecture of Japan’s traditional houses, where an abundance of beams and pillars provided an instant framework for tying. 

In our long-awaited Hashira series, @tamanduakinbaku will teach three variations of floor-based Hashira positions, two anchor point options, and present a mesmerising free-tying session and share his insights on the inspiration and intention to be found in the rigidity and restrictiveness of Hashira.

Floorplay tutorials and Anchor Points dropping Wednesday. Free-tying session coming up on Friday! And just because we’re not the type to leave you hanging (well, not too long anyway), here’s a teaser of what you can expect in the incredible free-tying video with model @mie.neko.rope✨

⭐️ Self Tying the Chest ⭐️

In this NEW series of tutorials, @missannabones teaches four chest ties suitable for solo-tying with her model… herself!

😍 While many Shibari Study harnesses can be adapted for self-tying, this four-part course is our first dedicated content focused specifically on self-tying and should give solo rope practitioners a far more nuanced insight as well as specialized tips and tricks for rope bondage without a partner.

📈 The first video eases into self-tying with a super easy pattern that keeps all the knots in the front of the tie. The second is little more challenging, with the knots in the back, while the third class steps things up again with extra decorative elements. The last video is the final boss and will challenge budding self-tyers with knots in the back as well as aesthetic additions.

💡We encourage all Shibari Study students, whether beginners or experienced in tying on others, to challenge yourself to this super fun series and perhaps even begin a new self-tying journey!

DEI* Monday Discussion: 

Quick Update on context: I want to take a moment to talk about context and intention as it’s been brought up in the comments. All of the DEI Monday posts are here to encourage reflective thinking - not about being right or wrong. I am not trying to be “right” or superior in these posts. The intention is to provide information, share resources and encourage collective dialogue and discourse. I am not perfect and I’m always open to feedback if the language or way I frame the context isn’t inviting that into the space. We are all a work in progress, myself and Shibari Study included.

In the context of the slides, I’d like to be very clear that having bias is a *natural* thing - not a *bad* thing - a thing that just is and exists. It’s how our brains naturally process and categorize information. Which is why it’s so important to check in with ourselves about them, because they manifest even if we don’t want them. Again, this isn’t a *bad* thing. This content is asking you to explore that with yourself and yourself questions about how those connections are made and show up. 💕

Let’s check in on biases and preferences! 🤔✅

Biases are a part of how everyone navigates the world. They are a part of our conscious and unconscious brain as we engage day to day. This post is just a *beginning* point for unpacking your own biases and unpacking if they impact how you develop your preferences. Please engage in the resources shared in the slides and feel free to share some of your own below! ⬇️ 

We’d love to be in community conversation with you! Check the last slides to share your thoughts in the comments! 🌿

As always, we welcome dialogue in the comments to discuss but ask that everyone please be kind and mindful of the language they are using if they disagree. This is a place to be in conversation and build community together through discourse. We welcome conflict or disagreement as an opportunity for deeper relationship building and also ask that you try to hold other perspectives to be true and valid at the same time as yours.

xo,
Sage 💕
@authenticallysage 

*Diversity, Equity and Inclusion
